        <div class="container">

            <!-- ═══ SECTION 1: OVERALL STRATEGY ═══ -->
            <section id="strategy">
                <div class="section-label">Section 01</div>
                <h2 contenteditable="true">Overall Strategy</h2>
                <p class="section-intro" contenteditable="true">The strategic direction that underpins every recommendation in this document.</p>

                <div class="strategy-box">
                    <h3>Strategic Thesis</h3>
                    <p contenteditable="true">Engagement must be elevated from a buried feature fragment to the central narrative of Habit Health's website. The repositioning flips the current hierarchy — from "health checks company that also has an app" to "engagement-first platform that drives measurable behavior change at scale." Every change targets one outcome: when an HR buyer evaluates Habit Health, Engagement is the first thing they see, understand, and remember — supported by proof, not promises.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="card-grid">
                    <div class="accent-card primary">
                        <h4>Core Problem</h4>
                        <p contenteditable="true">Engagement is invisible. It has no dedicated page, no navigation entry, no standalone messaging. An HR buyer would leave the site believing HCL Healthcare is a health-checks and clinics company. The most differentiated features (SPL, peer challenges, reward economy) exist only as barely legible text in small app mockups.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="accent-card secondary">
                        <h4>Strategic Outcome</h4>
                        <p contenteditable="true">A buyer exploring the site should reach the Engagement narrative within two clicks and understand in under 30 seconds: what it is, why it's different, and what outcomes it drives. The page should generate demo requests on its own, without a sales conversation.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="callout insight">
                    <div class="callout-title">Key Insight</div>
                    <p contenteditable="true">The corporate wellness market has shifted. HR buyers don't buy "features" — they buy participation rates, culture signals, and retention leverage. Every competitor page leads with outcomes. Habit Health currently leads with capabilities — and buries the best ones.</p>
                </div>
            </section>

            <div class="page-break"></div>

            <!-- ═══ SECTION 2: WEBSITE STRUCTURE ═══ -->
            <section id="structure">
                <div class="section-label">Section 02</div>
                <h2 contenteditable="true">Recommended Website Structure</h2>
                <p class="section-intro" contenteditable="true">How Engagement should be surfaced in navigation, information architecture, and page hierarchy.</p>

                <h3>Navigation Overhaul</h3>
                <p contenteditable="true">Engagement needs first-class citizenship in the primary navigation. The current "For Business" dropdown buries it entirely. The recommended restructure introduces a dedicated Engagement page and restructures the nav to match how HR buyers think — by outcome, not by service category.</p>

                <div class="card-grid">
                    <div class="card">
                        <h4 style="color: var(--accent-rose);">Current Navigation</h4>
                        <div class="sitemap">
                            <div class="sitemap-item level-0">For Business</div>
                            <div class="sitemap-item level-1">Our Solutions <span style="color:var(--accent-rose);font-size:11px;">⚠ broken</span></div>
                            <div class="sitemap-item level-1">Habit Health</div>
                            <div class="sitemap-item level-1">Onsite Health Centers</div>
                            <div class="sitemap-item level-1">Annual Health Checks</div>
                            <div class="sitemap-item level-1">Wellness Offerings</div>
                        </div>
                        <p style="font-size:12px;color:var(--text-muted);margin-top:8px;">Engagement is completely absent from navigation. "Our Solutions" page is broken.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="card">
                        <h4 style="color: var(--secondary);">Proposed Navigation</h4>
                        <div class="sitemap">
                            <div class="sitemap-item level-0">Platform</div>
                            <div class="sitemap-item level-1">Engagement <span class="new-badge">New</span> <span class="path">/engagement</span></div>
                            <div class="sitemap-item level-1">Habit Health App <span class="path">/habit-health</span></div>
                            <div class="sitemap-item level-1">Clinical & Preventive <span class="path">/clinical</span></div>
                            <div class="sitemap-item level-0" style="margin-top:12px;">Solutions</div>
                            <div class="sitemap-item level-1">For HR Leaders <span class="new-badge">New</span></div>
                            <div class="sitemap-item level-1">For Employees</div>
                        </div>
                        <p style="font-size:12px;color:var(--secondary);margin-top:8px;">Engagement becomes the first item under Platform — matching buyer priority.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <h3>Dedicated Engagement Page — Section Breakdown</h3>
                <p contenteditable="true">The new <code>/engagement</code> page should follow a narrative arc — from outcome hook to feature depth to proof. Each section has a specific job in the buyer's decision journey.</p>

                <div class="accent-card primary">
                    <h4>Section 1 — Hero (Above the Fold)</h4>
                    <p contenteditable="true"><strong>Job:</strong> Capture attention and establish the value proposition in 5 seconds.<br>
                    <strong>Content:</strong> Outcome-driven headline, 1-line subhead, single hero visual (animated dashboard or product screenshot showing live engagement), one primary CTA ("Book a Demo") and one secondary CTA ("See How It Works").<br>
                    <strong>Critical:</strong> No feature language above the fold. Lead with the business problem or outcome.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="accent-card secondary">
                    <h4>Section 2 — The Engagement Journey (Visual Flow)</h4>
                    <p contenteditable="true"><strong>Job:</strong> Show the complete engagement system as a coherent loop, not isolated features.<br>
                    <strong>Content:</strong> 4-step visual framework — Track → Compete → Learn → Earn — with brief descriptions and product screenshots for each stage. This becomes the organizing principle for the entire page.<br>
                    <strong>Critical:</strong> Must feel like a system, not a list. Arrows or flow lines connecting stages.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="accent-card amber">
                    <h4>Section 3 — Feature Deep-Dives (Tabbed or Scrollable)</h4>
                    <p contenteditable="true"><strong>Job:</strong> Give depth to each engagement pillar for buyers who want detail.<br>
                    <strong>Content:</strong> Four panels or tabs — Activity Tracking & Streaks, Challenges (Individual + SPL + CUG), Content & Webinars, Rewards & Incentives. Each with a product visual, 3–4 benefit bullets, and one metric or proof point.<br>
                    <strong>Critical:</strong> Name the unique features. "Steps Premier League" and "Peer Challenges" must appear as named concepts with explanations — not buried in screenshots.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="accent-card violet">
                    <h4>Section 4 — Outcomes & Social Proof</h4>
                    <p contenteditable="true"><strong>Job:</strong> Convert interest into confidence with evidence.<br>
                    <strong>Content:</strong> 2–3 outcome metrics (participation rates, engagement lift, completion %), 1–2 client quotes specifically about engagement, one mini case study (client name, challenge, result).<br>
                    <strong>Critical:</strong> If hard metrics aren't available yet, use directional stats from HCLT pilots. Even "8,000+ employees participated in SPL Season 1" is powerful.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="accent-card rose">
                    <h4>Section 5 — For HR Leaders (Role-Based Value)</h4>
                    <p contenteditable="true"><strong>Job:</strong> Speak directly to the buyer persona.<br>
                    <strong>Content:</strong> Two-column layout — left column: "What HR Gets" (dashboard screenshots, campaign setup, analytics), right column: "What Employees Experience" (app screenshots, leaderboards, rewards). Addresses both decision-maker and end-user.<br>
                    <strong>Critical:</strong> Show the admin experience. HR buyers need to see that setup is easy, not just that the employee experience is gamified.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="accent-card primary">
                    <h4>Section 6 — CTA + Integration Context</h4>
                    <p contenteditable="true"><strong>Job:</strong> Close the page with a strong action prompt.<br>
                    <strong>Content:</strong> Final CTA block ("See Engagement in Action — Book a Demo"), integration logos (Google Fit, Apple Health, wearables), brief mention of enterprise features (SSO, CUG-based configuration, multi-campus support).</p>
                </div>

                <h3>Homepage Changes</h3>
                <p contenteditable="true">The homepage requires three targeted changes. First, replace the default carousel slide — the app carousel should open on the Engagement screen (Steps Premier League or Active Zone), not Employee Health Benefits. Second, add an Engagement-specific section above the fold or immediately after the hero, with a headline, 1-line description, and "Learn More" link to /engagement. Third, update the "Holistic Wellbeing Solutions" circle to prominently feature "Employee Engagement" as a clickable path to the dedicated page.</p>
            </section>

            <div class="page-break"></div>

